					<div class="commentheading">On May 18, 2006 at 03:20 PM, Janka (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>forsting using butter and pudding</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody"><div class='commentquote'>Quote:<div class='commentquotebody'>The base was milk and flour, cooked together until creamy. Then you beat sugar and butter for about 10 minutes, until the sugar was incorporated into the butter. Add the cooled milk mixture and beat again.</div></div><br />
<br />
My familiy uses this kind of filling. However, I don't have the family recipe on hand. We use vanilla pudding powder.<br />
2 cups milk<br />
2 packages vanilla pudding powder (one package calling for 2 cups milk, so you get a thick custard)<br />
- cook until thick, let cool completely<br />
1 cup butter<br />
5-6 oz sugar<br />
- beat the butter and the sugar, then add the custard SLOWLY, until everything combines. The custard must be cold.<br />
Note: I did not try this recipe myself. You can add cocoa or vanilla flavor (if not using vanilla pudding). You'll need to adjust the amounts if using preserves or nuts, I suppose. Corn starch can also be used (see package for amounts).<br />
This spreads very well, and is not as "heavy" as only butter+sugar frosting.</div>
