					<div class="commentheading">On June 11, 2006 at 09:37 PM, Metrobake (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Buttercream</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">Use flash-pasteurized egg whites. These are in cartons in the refrigerated section of the grocery store, next to the egg substitutes. They look raw, but they aren't. The powdered egg whites are great for royal icing, but the refrigerated ones work better for meringues. Of course, really fresh eggs work best, but I'm not convinced that the sugar syrup effectively cooks the eggs (whip out your instant-read thermometer if you want to decide for yourself), so I use flash-pasteurized for my retail sales.   <br />
<br />
I, too, graduated from a "culinary" school, but in my case, it was a "baking/pastry" school. There is a difference. <br />
<br />
Regards,<br />
MB</div>
